TITLE: Rendering and Snapshot Testing a React Component with Jest (TypeScript)
DESCRIPTION: This code illustrates creating a snapshot test for a React component using Jest and react-test-renderer in TypeScript. The test renders a Link component, creates a serialized tree, and then compares it with a stored snapshot using toMatchSnapshot. Prerequisites include installing jest, react, and react-test-renderer, and the Link component must be either mocked or imported from the appropriate path. The main parameter is the rendered JSX for Link, with page prop. On first run, Jest generates the snapshot; on subsequent runs, any mismatch flags a test failure. Outputs are pass/fail test results and possibly new snapshot artifact files.
SOURCE: https://github.com/jestjs/jest/blob/main/website/versioned_docs/version-29.4/SnapshotTesting.md#2025-04-23_snippet_0

LANGUAGE: typescript
CODE:
```
import renderer from 'react-test-renderer';
import Link from '../Link';

it('renders correctly', () => {
  const tree = renderer
    .create(<Link page="http://www.facebook.com">Facebook</Link>)
    .toJSON();
  expect(tree).toMatchSnapshot();
});
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Negating Matchers in Jest Assertions (JavaScript)
DESCRIPTION: Demonstrates how to assert the negation of conditions within Jest tests using the 'not' modifier. Nested loops sum pairs of positive integers between 1 and 9, asserting that their sum is never zero. Requires Jest. Inputs are the range bounds; output is passing tests unless logic fails.
SOURCE: https://github.com/jestjs/jest/blob/main/website/versioned_docs/version-29.7/UsingMatchers.md#2025-04-23_snippet_2

LANGUAGE: JavaScript
CODE:
```
test('adding positive numbers is not zero', () => {
  for (let a = 1; a < 10; a++) {
    for (let b = 1; b < 10; b++) {
      expect(a + b).not.toBe(0);
    }
  }
});
```

