TITLE: Using Mock Return Values for Functional Testing (e.g., `filter`) in JavaScript
DESCRIPTION: This example shows how mock return values can be used effectively in functional programming styles, such as testing array filtering. A mock function `filterTestFn` is configured with `mockReturnValueOnce` to return `true` then `false`. This mock is used within an array's `filter` method to control which elements are included in the result, demonstrating value injection without complex stubs.
SOURCE: https://github.com/jestjs/jest/blob/main/website/versioned_docs/version-29.4/MockFunctions.md#2025-04-23_snippet_6

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
const filterTestFn = jest.fn();

// Make the mock return `true` for the first call,
// and `false` for the second call
filterTestFn.mockReturnValueOnce(true).mockReturnValueOnce(false);

const result = [11, 12].filter(num => filterTestFn(num));

console.log(result);
// > [11]
console.log(filterTestFn.mock.calls[0][0]); // 11
console.log(filterTestFn.mock.calls[1][0]); // 12
```

