TITLE: Utilizing New Built-in Matchers in Jest 23 (JavaScript)
DESCRIPTION: Showcases some of the new matchers introduced in Jest 23, providing enhanced assertion capabilities. Examples include checking specific call arguments (`nthCalledWith`), verifying return values (`toReturn`, `toReturnWith`, `lastReturnedWith`, `nthReturnedWith`), checking the number of returns (`toReturnTimes`), and performing strict equality checks (`toStrictEqual`).
SOURCE: https://github.com/jestjs/jest/blob/main/website/blog/2018-05-29-jest-23-blazing-fast-delightful-testing.md#2025-04-23_snippet_4

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
const mockFn = jest.fn(() => true).mockReturnValueOnce(false).mockReturnValueOnce('hello');

mockFn('arg1', 'arg2');
mockFn('arg3');
mockFn();

// New matcher examples
expect(mockFn).nthCalledWith(1, 'arg1', 'arg2');
expect(mockFn).toReturn(); // Checks if it returned (didn't throw) at least once
expect(mockFn).toReturnTimes(3);
expect(mockFn).toReturnWith(true); // Checks if it returned 'true' at least once
expect(mockFn).lastReturnedWith('hello');
expect(mockFn).nthReturnedWith(1, false); // Checks the return value of the 1st call

const obj1 = { a: 1, b: undefined };
const obj2 = { a: 1 };
expect(obj1).not.toEqual(obj2); // Standard equality considers undefined props
expect(obj1).toStrictEqual({ a: 1, b: undefined }); // Strict equality checks for undefined props
expect({ a: 1 }).toStrictEqual({ a: 1 });
```

