TITLE: Testing Object and Array Structure with Jest .toMatchObject - JavaScript
DESCRIPTION: Shows how to check that an object or an array of objects matches a subset of expected properties using Jest's .toMatchObject. Requires Jest and demonstrates flexible matching with asymmetric matchers for properties and array-level structural assertions. Inputs are objects or arrays, outputs are validations on subset matching and element correspondence.
SOURCE: https://github.com/jestjs/jest/blob/main/website/versioned_docs/version-29.7/ExpectAPI.md#2025-04-23_snippet_35

LANGUAGE: JavaScript
CODE:
```
const houseForSale = {
  bath: true,
  bedrooms: 4,
  kitchen: {
    amenities: ['oven', 'stove', 'washer'],
    area: 20,
    wallColor: 'white',
  },
};
const desiredHouse = {
  bath: true,
  kitchen: {
    amenities: ['oven', 'stove', 'washer'],
    wallColor: expect.stringMatching(/white|yellow/),
  },
};

test('the house has my desired features', () => {
  expect(houseForSale).toMatchObject(desiredHouse);
});
```

LANGUAGE: JavaScript
CODE:
```
describe('toMatchObject applied to arrays', () => {
  test('the number of elements must match exactly', () => {
    expect([{foo: 'bar'}, {baz: 1}]).toMatchObject([{foo: 'bar'}, {baz: 1}]);
  });

  test('.toMatchObject is called for each elements, so extra object properties are okay', () => {
    expect([{foo: 'bar'}, {baz: 1, extra: 'quux'}]).toMatchObject([
      {foo: 'bar'},
      {baz: 1},
    ]);
  });
});
```

